      "role": "assistant",
      "contents": [
        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "{\"week_number\":1,\"phase_type\":\"Base\",\"weekly_target_km\":10,\"is_deload_week\":false,\"days\":[{\"day_of_week\":0,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Full rest day. Let your body absorb the work from the week prior. Gentle foot mobility or calf stretching is fine if it feels good.\"},{\"day_of_week\":1,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"20-minute easy run at 5:58/km — the slower end of your easy range. Walk breaks are your friend here: if your foot speaks up at any point, take a 1–2 min walk break and continue. No heroics needed today.\"},{\"day_of_week\":2,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. Prioritize sleep and hydration. If your foot felt any discomfort yesterday, ice and elevate today.\"},{\"day_of_week\":3,\"slot_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"workout_type\":\"CrossTrain\",\"notes\":\"Optional low-impact cross-training — swimming, cycling, or pool running are all great choices. Keep it easy and under 30 minutes. Skip entirely if your foot needs more recovery.\"},{\"day_of_week\":4,\"slot_type\":\"Rest\",\"workout_type\":null,\"notes\":\"Rest day. Your body is rebuilding. This is productive time, not lost time.\"},{\"day_of_week\":5,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"Easy\",\"notes\":\"Second run of the week — 20 minutes at 5:58/km. Same approach as Monday: walk breaks if needed, no pushing through foot discomfort. Notice how your foot feels compared to Monday.\"},{\"day_of_week\":6,\"slot_type\":\"Run\",\"workout_type\":\"LongRun\",\"notes\":\"Your Saturday long run — 20 minutes easy at 5:45–5:58/km. This IS your long run for now, and that is completely appropriate for where you are. Consistency over distance, every time.\"}],\"week_summary\":\"Welcome back, James. Week 1 is about re-establishing a reliable three-day rhythm without asking more of your foot than it's ready to give. Your physiotherapist has cleared you for 20-minute easy runs only, and that's exactly what we're building around — not working around. Three runs of up to 20 minutes each puts you at roughly 10 km for the week, which is a meaningful and intentional step up from your recent 3 km weeks. Every run stays at the easy end of your pace range (5:45–5:58/km) — this isn't about fitness right now, it's about tissue tolerance and rebuilding the habit. Walk breaks are a tool, not a setback. If your foot gives you any signal during a run, use them. The optional Wednesday cross-train slot is there to support aerobic maintenance without loading the plantar fascia. How does this structure feel for your week?\"}"
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
